default&#xa0;default3.0default              defaultPlans being mdefaultade by NHS bodies to enable them to meet the Nicholson Challenge, and whether the NHS is succeeding in making efficiency gains rather that cuts. default&#xa0;default3.1
default              
defaultThe RCN accepts that the NHS needs to make financial efficiency savings due to the current economic climate. However, in far too many cases, as we have highlighted in previous submissions to the Committee, NHS bodies are making short term cuts to services 
defaultand personnel rather than well thought through, genuine efficiency savings. 
defaultThese cuts will, and are, inevitably affecting the quality of patient care. 
default&#xa0;
default3.2
default              
defaultThe RCN’s 
defaultFrontline First 
defaultcampaign collects and publishes data on cuts to NHS personnel and specif
defaultically nursing posts. The campaign calls for our members on the ground to tell us where they are seeing cuts to posts, where waste is eviden
defaultt
default and where innovations are developed. This information is the
defaultn
default robustly verified and analysed before it is publishe
defaultd. More recently the campaign has developed to use the Government’s own workforce figures. 
default&#xa0;
default3.3
default              
defaultAccording to the most recent data (for July 2013), the qualified nursing, midwifery and health visiting workforce lost 3,859 FTE roles (6,468 headcount) since 
defaultMay 2010, a decrease of 1.2 per cent.
default&#xa0;
defaultSupport to doctors and nursing staff, including roles such as health care assistants and assistant practitioners, has also decreased by a similar proportion, with 2,719 full time posts lost (7,058 headcount).
default&#xa0;
default3.4
default              
defaultAlt
defaulthough the aggregated qualified nursing, midwifery and health visiting workforce has decreased over the last three years, the picture is more complex than this. Workforce numbers for both qualified midwives and qualified health visitors have actually increa
defaultsed. The midwifery workforce has increased by 1,311 FTE roles since May 2010, and the health visiting workforce has increased by 700 FTE roles.
default These figures, however, blur the effect of cuts to the nursing workforce.
default If these figures are removed from the 
defaultaggregated data, it indicates a
default&#xa0;
defaulttrue fall of 5,870 FTE nurse roles (or 7,578 headcount) since May 2010
default.
default&#xa0;
default3.5
default              
defaultAlthough the nursing workforce has decreased overall, posts have been lost from different services at varying rates. The RCN is extremely concerne
defaultd that the areas which have seen the greatest proportional workforce losses are also those where investment is urgently needed.
default&#xa0;
default3.6
default              
defaultIn mental health services, the workforce has seen a decrease of nearly 2,000 full time nursing staff since 2010.
default&#xa0;
defaultThis is de
defaultspite years of rising demand for mental health care. In England, 48,631 people were detained in hospital for assessment and/or treatment of 
defaulta 
defaultmental disorder under the Mental Health Act in 2011/2012, and a further 4,220 
defaultpatients were subject to community t
defaultreatment orders (CTOs) – a 5
default per cent
default increase in detentions and 10
default per cent
default increase in CTOs compared to the previous year. Mental health services are now showing increasing levels of strain, with evidence suggesting 
defaultthat 
defaultat least 1,711 mental health beds
default (9 per
default 
defaultcent of the total) were closed between April 2011 and August 2013.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe learning disability nursing workforce has also seen significant long term decline, with 800 full time roles lost since 2010, a fall of around 15 per cent.
default&#xa0;
default3.7
default              
defaultAfter a decade of
default workforce expansion, peaking in 2009-2010,
default the 
defaultcommunity
default nursing workforce has in 
defaultthe last three years seen a fall of 1,744 full time roles, or 3.6 per cent of the workforce.
default&#xa0;
defaultDespite rhetoric of a shift from acute to community models of care, the proporti
defaulton of nurses working in community services has changed very little, from 14.3
default per cent
default of the total nursing workforce in 2002, to 15.1 per cent in 2012.
default&#xa0;
defaultLosses have been particularly acute in the district nursing workforce, which has been declining year on
default year for the last decade, with 1,312 full time posts lost since 2010 (a 17 per cent decrease).
default&#xa0;
default3.8
default              
defaultIn addition to those posts lost so far, the RCN’s 2012 report on the community nursing workforce identified that services would suffer disproportionately 
defaultmore from an ag
defaulte
defaulting nursing workforce.
default&#xa0;
defaultIn the community workforce, 38 per cent of nurses were found to be aged 50 and over, compared to 23.6 per cent of the acute, 
defaultolder people
default and general nursing workforce.
default&#xa0;
defaultWith 59.2 per cent of the community nursing work
defaultforce aged 45 and over, a large proportion will reach 
defaultretirement age
default in the next decade
default, compounding the urgent need to build the community w
defaultorkforce capacity in the future
default.
default&#xa0;
default3.9
default              
defaultThe RCN is 
defaultalso 
defaultaware
default, through intelligence and information gathered,
default of many NHS trusts which have instigated recruitment freezes and 
defaultdelete 
defaultvacancies so that they can reduce their wage bill through 
default‘
defaultnatural wastage
default’ and avoid making direct job cuts
default.
default This obviously has a negative effect on the level of service that can be 
defaultprovided. 
default&#xa0;
default3.10
default              
defaultNursing posts are also being downbanded, 
defaultwhere nursing staff are having to accept the reg
defaultra
defaultding of their jobs. It is also where 
defaultexperienced qualified nursing posts 
defaultare replaced 
defaultwith those of a lower band or unregistered health care assista
defaultnts. The RCN has repeatedly drawn attention to these issues and the risk to patient safety they represent. 
default&#xa0;
default3.11
default              
defaultNurse staffing levels and skill mix have a direct impact on the health outcomes that can be achieved. 
defaultThe Government should mandate the use of
default staffing levels tools
default which allow for local flexibility and variability
default. In too many cases we are seeing patients suffer because of inadequate nurse staffing levels. In 
defaultseveral
default recent 
defaultGovernment commissioned reports this correlation 
defaultbetween nurse staffing
default levels and patient outcomes has been 
defaultidentified; most recently by Sir Bruce Keogh in his review of 14 NHS trust with above average outliers in mortality rates
default. These trusts were put under ‘special measures’ with all of them undertaking urgent reviews of t
defaultheir nurse staffing levels. 
defaultIt is clear that these strains have been brought about by financial constraint. 
defaultStaffing levels and skill mix must be planned and based on a sound clinical rationale, not budget availability.
default&#xa0;
default3.12
default              
defaultThere is now an overwhelming e
defaultvidence base for the use of mandatory safe staffing levels; it is now time to act on this evidence. 
default&#xa0;
default4.0default              defaultEffectiveness of the mechanisms by which resources are distributed geographically in the NHS.default&#xa0;
default4.1
default              
defaultNHS England is currently reviewing the funding 
defaultallocation formula that is used to allocate funds to CCGs across England
default.The proposed revisions to the allocation formula mean that there will be no weighting for levels of deprivation in local areas, or which have poor health outcomes. Instead, the new a
defaultllocation formula will be based on the predicted demand for health
default 
defaultcare for the population as a whole. Some of the biggest losers in terms of NHS funding cover the same areas of the country where we have the highest incidences of chronic and long-term illn
defaultess.
default&#xa0;
default4.2
default              
defaultResearch published by the HSJ and the University of Liverpool on 7th October 2013 shows that, under the new proposed formula
default:
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default4.3
default              
defaultThe RCN is committed to reducing inequalities in access to health care. The 
defaultRCN
default believes that the funding allocation should continue to have a
default 
defaultmixed 
defaultsystem of weighting to reflect levels of deprivation 
defaultand also the age of populations 
defaultin local areas, or which have poor health outcomes.  
default&#xa0;
default5.0default              defaultProspects for the long-term viability of NHS trusts and NHS foundation trusts. default&#xa0;default5.1
default              
defaultThe NHS continues t
defaulto face one of the most significant financial challenges in its history. The anticipated continuation 
defaultand increase 
defaultof costs saving measures within the NHS beyond 2014/15 will inevitably result in even further pressures on the delivery of services. The RCN h
defaultas consistently highlighted that current funding is unlikely to meet the costs of the rising health demand.
default&#xa0;
default5.2
default              
defaultDespite the stated intentions of politicians, health experts and NHS mangers to move services from acute hospitals into the community, both to 
defaultreduce costs and to have more person-centred care, the RCN on the whole has found very little clear evidence of this shift actually happening on the ground. 
defaultMoving care away from secondary settings in to the community must be seen as key to achieving meani
defaultngful efficiencies and service redesign. 
default&#xa0;
default5.3
default              
defaultThe RCN believes that NHS organisations need to work together to provide real service transformation that brings care closer to home and integrates care around the patient. This can result in efficiency savings and benefit patients, but will require co-ope
defaultration between trusts and investment in the short-term. 
default&#xa0;
default6.0default              defaultThe impact on the provision of adult social care of the 2010 spending review settlement and the ability of local authorities to make the necessary efficiency savingsdefault&#xa0;
default6.1
default              
defaultThe King’s Fund reports
default that l
defaultocal authority spending on social care has fallen for four years in succession, and fewer people are using publicly funded care than ever before. With 87 per cent of local authorities setting their eligibility criteria at substantial or higher, it h
defaultas become much harder for people 
defaultto access care
default.
default 
default&#xa0;
default6.2
default              
defaultR
defaulteducing the spending on social care  will inevitably 
defaultlead to an increase in need and also the further complication of individuals requiring care. The NHS and nursing staff, both in acute and communit
defaulty settings, are then required to fill the growing gaps in social care provision for patients with increasingly complex conditions.
default 75
default per cent
default 
defaultof RCN members responding to a 2012 survey on community nursing said that the pressure on their team had increase
defaultd as a result of cuts to
default social care provision made by l
defaultoca
