default6.3
default              
defaultReadmissions
default,
default or the so-called ‘revolving door’
default,
default are a result of insufficient support in social care or community settings. Nursing staff
default frequently
default experience the frustratio
defaultn of seeing a healthy patient discharged into community care, only to see them 
defaultreadmitted into acute setting
defaults
default weeks down the line owing to the absence of appropriate community care.  
default&#xa0;
default6.4
default              
defaultThe Care Quality Commission’s 
defaultThe state of health and adult social 
defaultcare in England: an overview of key themes in care in 2011/12
default found that 
defaultif discharge arrangements and planning for discharge are not sufficient, there is an increased risk of emergency readmission,
default the national average for emergency readmissions within 0-
default7 days of discharge that required at least an overnight stay was 2.5 per cent, but this increased to  3.8 per cent
default 
defaultfor emergency readmissions within 8-30 days, where external factors were more likely to contribute to the readmission.
default&#xa0;
default6.5
default              
defaultA recent report 
defaultfrom the Nuffield Trust and Health Foundation illustrated what we are hearing from our members. It showed that the number of elderly patients who have been readmitted following early discharge has risen from 3,658 in 2001/2 to 6,810 in 2010/11, a rise of 6
default9 per cent. The report also showed that the situation had worsened in the last three years
default. 
default&#xa0;
default6.6
default              
defaultDelayed discharge figures can be used to quantify the levels of pick up by the NHS of social care needs.  On any one day a significant number of patients (ap
defaultprox
defaultimately
default 4,000 in England), mostly over the age of 75, are being cared for on an acute ward in hospital when they could be cared for in the community.  In 60
default per cent
default of these 
defaultcases it is
default caused by social services failing to meet their responsibilities
default;
default 
default they are either not assessing the patient for community care or cannot provide the care the patient needs to be able to leave the acute care setting
