default8.0default              defaultProgress on making efficiencies through the integration of health and social care servicesdefault&#xa0;default8.1
default              
defaultIntegra
defaulttion of health and social care services is not only seen as providing patients with
default timely access to seamless care, but also a way of eliminating costly duplication of services and ensuring patients are given the care 
defaultthey need in the right setting.
default Howeve
defaultr, integration of health and social care services in England is still very much piece meal an
defaultd individually programme based.
default 
default&#xa0;
default8.2
default              
defaultWhile there are many excellent examples of integrated care delivery across the country, including specific teams, projects an
defaultd processes, many of which are led or designed by nurses, there is a wide variation.
default Some examples have been enabled by the development of NHS Care Trusts, integrated or pooled budgets, and the Department of Health’s Health and Social Care Integration Pro
defaultgramme (HSCIP)
default. However, there have been inconsistencies in policy and project implementation with no significant learning mechanisms in place or application of best practice.
default We hope that the Government programme of integration ‘Pioneers’ is successful i
defaultn developing a tangible way forward in this area. 
default&#xa0;
default8.3
default              
defaultFunding issues also impact on the ability to integrate services, as RCN members are increasingly informing us, multi-disciplinary teams are being left short of critical impact from social workers and 
defaultother disciplines owing to budgetary cuts.  This means that patients with complex needs are not benefiting from crucial multi-disciplinary 
defaultservices
default, which look at their needs
default holistically
default and aim to ensure that their patient journey is smooth.
default     
default&#xa0;
default8.4
default              
defaultD
defaultespite the notable effort of nursing and other care professionals, the structures, processes and systems in place have not consistently been designed around the service 
defaultuser to allow integrated care. 
